Exercise 1 - Pareto Distribution

The Pareto distribution has a cdf given by the formula \[F_X(x;\alpha,\beta)=\begin{cases}1-(\frac{\beta}{x})^{\alpha}&x>\beta\\0&x\le\beta\end{cases}\] In the above, the parameters \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\) are both assumed to be positive, with \(\alpha\) being called the shape parameter and \(\beta\) being called the scale parameter. Note that the support of this distribution depends on the value of \(\beta\).

ppareto function

Write a function ppareto which implements the above formula for the cdf. This function should take the arguments x, shape (i.e. \(\alpha\)), scale (i.e. \(\beta\)), along with an argument lower.tail. There should be a default argument of scale = 1 and also a default argument of lower.tail = TRUE. When lower.tail = FALSE is passed to your function, it should return \(1-F_X(x)\) instead of \(F_X(x)\).

ppareto = function(x, shape, scale = 1, lower.tail = TRUE ) {
#cdf for the Pareto Distribution
  
  if( x > scale){
    Fx = 1 - ((scale/x)^shape)
  }
  else{
    Fx = 0
  }
  
  if(lower.tail == TRUE) {
    Final_Fx = Fx
  } else if(lower.tail == FALSE) {
    Final_Fx = 1 - Fx
  }
  
  return (Final_Fx)
}

dpareto function

Determine what the pdf of this distribution should be, recalling that \[f_X(x)=\frac{d}{dx}\,F_X(x)\] If need be, use Mathematica or other tools to help you with this differentiation problem.

Implement a function for the pdf and call it dpareto. Make sure this function takes the arguments x, shape (\(\alpha\)), and scale (\(\beta\)), with a default argument of 1 for the scale parameter.

dpareto = function(x, shape, scale = 1){
#pdf for the Pareto Distribution

  Final_Fx = ifelse(x<scale, 0, (shape * (scale^shape)) / x^(shape + 1))
# for the ifelse https://www.statology.org/r-condition-has-length-1-only-first-element-will-be-used/
  
  return (Final_Fx)
}

qpareto function

Determine the quantile function \(F^{-1}(x)\) for this distribution and implement this as an R function called qpareto. This function should take the arguments p, shape, scale = 1, and also lower.tail = TRUE. When the argument lower.tail = FALSE is passed to the function, it should return the value of an upper quantile (i.e. the \(1-p\) quantile).

qpareto = function(p, shape, scale = 1, lower.tail = TRUE){
#quantile for the Pareto Distribution
  
  #print(p)
  if(lower.tail == TRUE){
    F_Inv = scale * (1/(1 - p)^(1/shape))
  }
  else{
    F_Inv = 1 - (scale * (1/(1 - p)^(1/shape)))
  }
  
  return (F_Inv)
}

rpareto function

Implement a function rpareto which generates a sample of \(n\) variates from the Pareto distribution. This function should take the arguments n, shape, and scale (with the default value of 1 for scale).

rpareto = function(n, shape, scale = 1){

  return(qpareto(runif(n), shape, scale))
}

Exercise 2 - Frechet Distribution

The Frechet distribution has a pdf and cdf given by the formulas \[f_X(x;\alpha,\mu,\sigma)=\frac{\alpha}{\sigma}\left(\frac{x-\mu}{\sigma}\right)^{-(\alpha+1)}\,e^{-(\frac{x-\mu}{\sigma})^{-\alpha}},\ x>\mu\] and \[F_X(x;\alpha,\mu,\sigma)=\begin{cases}e^{-(\frac{x-\mu}{\sigma})^{-\alpha}}&x>\mu\\0&x\le\mu\end{cases}\] The parameters \(\alpha\), \(\mu\), and \(\sigma\) are called the shape, location, and scale parameters, respectively.

dfrechet and pfrechet functions

pfrechet = function(x,shape, location = 0, scale = 1){
#CDF of Frechet Distribution

  Fx = ifelse(x<= location, 0 ,exp(1)^(-(x - location)/scale)^(-shape))
  
  return(Fx)
}
dfrechet = function(x, shape, location = 0, scale = 1){
#PDF of Frechet Distribution

  fx = ifelse( x<=location, 0 , shape/scale *  ( (x - location)/scale)^(-(shape + 1)) * 
                 exp(-((x - location)/scale)^(-shape)))
  
  return(fx)
}

Write R functions which implement the pdf and cdf of this distribution. Your functions should take the arguments x, shape (\(\alpha\)), along with arguments taking the default values location = 0 (\(\mu\)) and scale = 1 (\(\sigma\)). Make sure these functions return a value of 0 when \(x<\mu\).

Create some plots of the pdf for varying values of \(\alpha\) while keeping the location (\(\mu\)) and scale (\(\sigma\)) parameters fixed at their default values.

qfrechet function

Implement the quantile function for the Frechet distribution, calling this function qfrechet. It should take the arguments p, shape, location, and scale (with location = 0 and scale = 1 being default arguments). The median of this distribution can be shown to be \[\mu+\sigma\left(\ln(2)\right)^{-1/\alpha}\] Verify that your qfrechet function is implemented correctly by calculating the median with qfrechet and checking it with the above formula for a few values of \(\alpha\) (you can keep \(\mu=0\) and \(\sigma=1\)).

qfrechet = function(p, shape, location = 0, scale = 1){
#quantile function for Frechet Distribution
  q = location + (scale * ( (-1/log(p))^(1/shape) ) )
  return(q)
}

#median
shape_values = c(1, 2, 3)  # Different shape values
location = 0
scale = 1

qfrechet(0.5, shape_values, location, scale)
## [1] 1.442695 1.201122 1.129947
frechet_median = location + scale * (log(2))^(-1/shape_values)
frechet_median
## [1] 1.442695 1.201122 1.129947

Exercise 3 - Discrete Distribution

Suppose that a discrete random variable \(X\) has the pmf as stated in the table below:

\(x\) 0 1 2 3 4 5
\(f_X(x)\) 0.05 0.1 0.15 0.4 0.15 0.15

rdiscrete function

Write a function, call it rdiscrete for lack of a better choice, which generates a random sample of \(n\) variates from this distribution using the inverse transform method (i.e. do not just use the sample function). This function need only take the argument n, though for an interesting challenge you might consider allowing the function to further take the arguments x and prob, which would be vectors of the possible values of \(X\) and their associated probabilities.

#Dicrete Distribution
library("dplyr")   
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
rdiscrete = function(n){
  
  x = c(-1, 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5)
  fx = c(0, 0.05, 0.1, 0.15, 0.4, 0.15, 0.15)
  
  rand =runif(n)
  sum_fx = cumsum(fx)
  R_fx = c()
  
for (i in rand)  {
  for (j in 1:length(sum_fx) ){
  if (between(i, sum_fx[j], sum_fx[j+1])){ #dplyr used for the between function
  R_fx = c(R_fx, x[j+1])
}
}
}

return(data.frame(rand, R_fx)) 

}
